-- Grains, Soybeans Drop on European Crisis: Commodities at Close
-- B y   T o m   M e t c a l f
-- 2012-07-24T16:23:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-24/grains-soybeans-drop-on-european-crisis-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities fell 1.1 percent to 626.40 by 5.22 p.m. in
London. The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials was
down 1.5 percent at 1,520.0215.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS:  Corn and soybean futures tumbled for the second straight
day on speculation that mounting European economic woes will
erode commodity demand, and rain forecast in the U.S. this week
may boost crops. Wheat also dropped.  Corn futures for December delivery fell 2.9 percent to
$7.625 a bushel on the  Chicago  Board of Trade. Yesterday, the
price closed down 1.3 percent after reaching a record $8.  Soybean futures for November delivery slumped 3 percent to
$15.7325 a bushel. Yesterday, the price settled down 3.8 percent
after climbing to an all-time high of $16.915.  Wheat futures for September delivery fell 4.1 percent to
$8.7525 a bushel. A close at that price would mark the biggest
drop for a most-active contract since June 1. Yesterday, the
grain declined 3.2 percent.  Grain markets: NI GRMKTS  NATURAL GAS  U.K. natural gas for delivery today pared an advance as
imports from  Norway  increased.  Within-day gas was 1.1 percent higher at 53.3 pence a
therm, after rising to 54 pence a therm earlier, according to
broker data compiled by Bloomberg.  U.K. natural gas: NI NUKMKT Gas market: NI GASMARKET Americas
natural gas: NI AGASMARKET European natural gas: NI EGASMARKET  SOFT COMMODITIES  Sugar prices fell for a second day on concern that the
crisis in  Europe  will crimp demand and amid signs of rising
supplies. Coffee and cocoa also declined. Cotton and orange
juice rose.  Raw sugar for October delivery fell 0.1 percent to 23.86
cents a pound on ICE Futures U.S. in  New York , after slipping as
much as 1.2 percent. Yesterday, prices settled 0.1 percent lower
after touching 24 cents, the highest since March 29.  Also, on the ICE, arabica-coffee futures for September
delivery declined 0.1 percent to $1.8495 a pound in New York,
while cocoa for September delivery fell 0.7 percent to $2,223 a
metric ton.  Cotton futures for December delivery advanced 0.3 percent
to 72.43 cents a pound, after slipping 0.6 percent. Orange-juice
futures for September delivery gained 3.1 percent to $1.128 a
pound in New York, heading for the first gain after a 10-session
slump.  Soft  commodities markets : NI SOMKTS  CRUDE OIL  Oil rose for the first time in three days as clashes in
 Syria  raised tension in the  Middle East  and as  China ’s
manufacturing may contract at a slower pace in July.  Crude oil for September delivery rose 31 cents, or 0.4
percent, to $88.45 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
Prices are down 11 percent this year.  Brent oil for September settlement increased 4 cents to
$103.30 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures Europe
exchange.  Oil markets: NI OILMARKET  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline fell on concern that Europe’s fiscal crisis is
worsening as euro-area manufacturing contracted and Moody’s
Investors Service cut the credit outlook for  Germany .  August-delivery gasoline fell 2.05 cents, or 0.7 percent,
to $2.8624 a gallon on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . The
more actively traded September contract lost 1.05 cents to
$2.7533 a gallon.  August-delivery heating oil rose 0.15 cent to $2.8204 a
gallon, after falling as low as $2.7968. The more actively
traded September contract gained 0.25 cent to $2.8231.  Regular gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide,
increased 0.6 cent to $3.477 a gallon, according to AAA. Prices
are the highest since June 19, and are down 12 percent from a
year-to-date high of $3.936 on April 4.  Oil Products Europe: NI OPEMKT Gasoline: NI GASOLINE Heating
oil: NI HEATOIL  BASE METALS  Copper fell for a third straight session in New York as a
cut in Germany’s debt-ratings outlook was another signal that
the euro-area financial crisis may pinch metals demand.  Copper futures for September delivery slid 0.6 percent to
$3.36 a pound on the Comex in New York. The metal dropped 4.4
percent in the previous two sessions.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three-
months rose 0.1 percent to $7,408 a metric ton ($3.36 a pound).  Aluminum, zinc, lead and tin fell in London. Nickel
advanced.  Base metals markets: NI BMMKTS  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold futures for August delivery were down 10 cents at
$1,577.30 an ounce on the Comex in New York, after rising as
much as 0.4 percent.  Silver futures for September delivery fell 0.3 percent to
$26.96 an ounce in New York.  Precious metal markets: NI PCMKTS  LIVESTOCK  Cattle futures fell on speculation that U.S. ranchers will
slaughter more of their herds, boosting beef supplies, as
drought damages pastures and increases feed costs. Hog prices
also declined.  Cattle futures for October delivery dropped 0.4 percent to
$1.23 a pound on the Chicago  Mercantile Exchange. Prices were
up 1.7 percent this year through yesterday.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement increased 0.7
percent to $1.36575 a pound on the CME.  Hog futures for October settlement fell 0.6 percent to
78.35 cents a pound in Chicago. Prices slumped 6.5 percent this
year through yesterday.  Livestock markets: NI LVMKTS  EUROPEAN CARBON PERMITS  European Union carbon for December rose 0.7 percent, to
7.18 euros ($8.66) on the ICE Futures Europe exchange in London.  EU  Carbon Emissions : NI ECBMKT  To contact the reporter on this story:
